C++ on Desktop/Server field.

Yes. Most of the fields I mentioned are primarily desktop, workstation, cloud, or server-side C++ — not traditional embedded firmware work.

Roughly:

* Desktop/PC applications
  Qt apps, CAD software, IDEs, media tools, engineering software
  → Windows/Linux/macOS desktop

* Server/backend systems
  Trading systems, databases, distributed systems, networking services
  → Linux servers/cloud/datacenters

* Infrastructure/software platforms
  Browsers, compilers, storage engines, virtualization software
  → Mostly PC/server environments

* Game engines/graphics
  PC/console development

* Scientific/simulation software
  HPC clusters, Linux workstations, servers

Embedded C++ is different in daily work style. It usually involves:

* microcontrollers
* device drivers
* RTOS
* hardware protocols
* memory constraints
* board bring-up
* firmware flashing
* oscilloscopes/JTAG

Your current experience actually looks closer to:

* Linux application development
* Qt desktop UI
* backend/service logic
* systems programming

than bare-metal embedded.

For example:

* QML + QAbstractListModel + controllers + async tasks
* Linux tooling
* Docker
* networking
* JSON parsing
* architecture discussions

These are much more common in desktop/server-side C++ engineering than in low-level firmware jobs.

There is also a middle area called “embedded Linux application development”:

* medical devices
* industrial machines
* automotive HMIs
* instruments
* kiosks

There people still use:

* Linux
* Qt
* C++
* networking
* multithreading

But the application layer feels very similar to desktop/server C++ development.

So you are not locked into embedded at all. Your current skill direction can transition naturally into:

* Qt desktop engineer
* Linux C++ engineer
* backend C++ developer
* systems software engineer
* platform/tooling engineer

without needing microcontroller firmware expertise.